Grass Silage Mineral Bulletin 2019

 
October 21 / 2019
 
By Admin
Here's a look at the key headlines from our Grass Silage Mineral Bulletin 2019 - 

·  MACRO-MINERALS UNCHANGED OVER PAST 3 SEASONS EXCEPT FOR ELECTROLYTES

· ELECTROLYTE ELEMENTS (POTASSIUM, SODIUM, CHLORIDE) HIGHER DUE TO WARMER SPRING

· CATION-ANION BALANCE RISES TO +423 meq/kg

· SOIL CONTAMINATION SUBSTANTIALLY LOWER, REFLECTING GOOD CONDITIONS AT GRASS HARVESTING

· MOLYBDENUM FALLS DRAMATICALLY (20%) AS MAY DRIER THAN AVERAGE

· HYPOCALCAEMIA RISK INCREASED, BUT ANTAGONISTIC CHALLENGE TO COW FERTILITY AND HEALTH REDUCED

Grass Silage Mineral Bulletin 2018

 
November 19 / 2018
 
By Admin
Looking forward to catching up with everyone at AgriScot on Wednesday 21th of November Stand 16 in the Highland Hall.

In the mean time please find our Grass Silage Mineral Profile Bulletin attached here!


Key Headlines from the Bulletin:

• Macro minerals similar to 2017 except electrolyte elements.

• Potassium (2.73%), Sodium (0.25%), Chloride (0.98%) reduced due to soil water deficit.

• Cation-anion balance steady at +381 meq/kg.

• Soil contamination marginally reduced but iron higher at 427mg/kg.

• Molybdenum continues to climb at 1.91mg/kg due to wet spring.

• Relative Copper antagonism remains high.

Grass Silage Mineral Bulletin 2017

 
September 18 / 2017
 
By Admin
Great to catch up with everyone at the UK Dairy Day! You can next catch us at AgriScot on Wednesday 15th of November.

In the mean time please find our Grass Silage Mineral Profile Bulletin attached here!


Key Headlines from the Bulletin:

· Phosphorus steady at 0.36% - up 38% since 2010.


· Potassium reports slight increase to 2.80% but remains lower than peak in 2013/14.


· Cation-anion balance follows Potassium trend and is similar to 2016 high value at +391 meq/kg.


· Soil contamination similar to 2016, as reflected in Iron level of 401mg/kg, but down from 2014 peak.


· Molybdenum up again to 1.71mg/kg - has increased by 33% since 2010.


· Relative Copper antagonism remains high.


 

 

Grass Silage Mineral Profile 2016

 
September 20 / 2016
 
By Admin
Please find our Grass Silage Mineral Profile Bulletin for 2016 attached here!





Key Headlines from the Bulletin:

· Phosphorus continues to increase - up 30% since 2010

· Potassium declines from high in early part of this decade as fertiliser inputs are reduced.

· Cation-anion balance follows potassium trend.

· Sulphur up by 27% since 2010 due to focus on adding Sulphur to grassland fertiliser.

· Soil contamination similar to 2015, but down from 2014 peak.

· Molybdenum up again - has increased by 22% since 2010.

· Relative Copper antagonism remains significant.
 

Magnesium Bulletin

 
April 15 / 2015
 
By Admin
Although temperatures remain cool spring has defiantly arrived with its attendant risk factors for cattle turned out to grass. Taking action to minimise the risk of staggers (hypomagnesaemia) remains a key strategy, with the provision of a palatable source of Magnesium being paramount. High forage Potassium is the most significant nutritional suppressor of Magnesium absorption.

The attached bulletin highlights the relationship between Potassium and Magnesium and those actions which are important to reducing the risk of staggers.

Download the full bulletin here.

The Mineral Specialists

 
January 24 / 2014
 
By Admin
Strong relationships exist in the natural world between the mineral nutrition of soils, plants and animals, including humans. Although we are primarily interested in mineral nutrition of farm animals, dietary mineral supply depends on the composition of forages and feedingstuffs. These are obviously influenced by the soil and rocks from which they come, so to better understand animal mineral nutrition it is necessary to look at the natural mineral cycle to ensure the dietary mineral supply offered is both optimal and well-balanced in content.

GRASS SILAGE 2013 - MINERAL PROFILE

 
September 20 / 2013
 
By Admin
What a difference a year makes! Last year’s early warm spring followed by almost continual summer rainfall resulted in reduced yields of lower quality silage which had an extremely adverse mineral profile for cow health and productivity. This year didn’t start much better as spring temperatures were well below average, with March recording a 3°C average lower temperature compared to the 1981-2010 mean.

PROTECTED MINERALS

 
January 11 / 2013
 
By Admin
Protected minerals are today a common feature of the feed additive market. Although many different products are being promoted, they can broadly be placed in one of four categories:

> Metal Amino Acid Chelates (MAAC)
Novus (Albion)

> Metal Proteinates
Alltech, Optimins, Key Minerals

> Metal Amino Acid Complexes
Zinpro

> Metal Polysaccharide Complexes
Qualitech

Indeed, these are the categories used by the American Association of Feed Control Officials (AAFCO) to differentiate between the many products in the market place. In the EU the situation is different in that each product has to receive separate approval for inclusion on a positive list for each trace element.

Download and read the full bulletin here...
